And I'm Becca

5
00:00:13.000 --> 00:00:17.000
In this episode, we're discussing a food seasoning that's so popular

6
00:00:17.000 --> 00:00:21.000
We eat around 3-quarters of a million tons of it a year

7
00:00:21.000 --> 00:00:23.000
We're talking about pepper

8
00:00:23.000 --> 00:00:25.000
Do you add pepper to your food, Becca?

9
00:00:25.000 --> 00:00:29.000
I do know, yes, I think it's an easy way to add some spice

10
00:00:30.000 --> 00:00:34.000
Yeah, I love a bit of pepper, I grind pepper on to everything

11
00:00:34.000 --> 00:00:35.000
Well, everything

12
00:00:35.000 --> 00:00:37.000
But I do like it

13
00:00:37.000 --> 00:00:42.000
Given its popularity, it's surprising that most people know very little about pepper

14
00:00:42.000 --> 00:00:46.000
Did you know, for example, that peppers are the fruit of vines

15
00:00:46.000 --> 00:00:49.000
Often growing over 10 meters high

16
00:00:49.000 --> 00:00:52.000
Our ancestors would be surprised how little we know

17
00:00:52.000 --> 00:00:57.000
From ancient Greece onwards, pepper was prized as the black gold of ingredients

18
00:00:57.000 --> 00:01:00.000
And explorers cross oceans in search of it

19
00:01:00.000 --> 00:01:02.000
Discovering new continents along the way

20
00:01:02.000 --> 00:01:05.000
In this episode, we'll get re-acquainted with pepper

21
00:01:05.000 --> 00:01:08.000
And learn some useful new words and phrases too

22
00:01:08.000 --> 00:01:12.000
And remember, you'll find a transcript for you to read along with us

23
00:01:12.000 --> 00:01:16.000
As you listen on our website, BBCLearningEnglish.com

24
00:01:16.000 --> 00:01:20.000
Okay, first I have a question for you, of course Becca

25
00:01:20.000 --> 00:01:25.000
Although it's black pepper, you're most likely to see in shops and restaurants in the UK

26
00:01:25.000 --> 00:01:28.000
There are hundreds of different varieties worldwide

27
00:01:28.000 --> 00:01:33.000
But what is unusual about food quark, a white pepper from Vietnam

28
00:01:33.000 --> 00:01:36.000
Does it a make people cry?

29
00:01:36.000 --> 00:01:41.000
B tastes like parmesan cheese or sea, costs more than gold

30
00:01:41.000 --> 00:01:45.000
Hmm, well, I don't think it would be as expensive as gold

31
00:01:45.000 --> 00:01:48.000
And I kind of want it to taste like parmesan cheese

32
00:01:48.000 --> 00:01:52.000
Okay, well, we'll find out later in the program

33
00:01:52.000 --> 00:01:58.000
Matilda Rollinger is the daughter of Olivier Rollinger, an award-winning French chef

34
00:01:58.000 --> 00:02:00.000
Famous for his use of spices

35
00:02:00.000 --> 00:02:05.000
While other little girls of her age were sprinkling sugar on their breakfast yogurt

36
00:02:05.000 --> 00:02:09.000
Matilda was the only girl in Paris sprinkling pepper

37
00:02:09.000 --> 00:02:15.000
Today, Matilda runs the apiece rolling a spice shop in the opera area of the city

38
00:02:15.000 --> 00:02:18.000
Here customers can find a huge range of peppers

39
00:02:18.000 --> 00:02:25.000
From fruity red camboding camp pot pepper to Borneo's Sarawak black pepper with its Woody aroma

40
00:02:25.000 --> 00:02:28.000
These peppers have strong distinctive tastes

41
00:02:28.000 --> 00:02:34.000
But curiously, they enhance rather than overpower the flavour of the food you're eating

42
00:02:34.000 --> 00:02:38.000
As Matilda explained to BBC World Service program the food chain

43
00:02:38.000 --> 00:02:45.000
It will give a kick and transform it, but you will still have the flavour of the different ingredients

44
00:02:45.000 --> 00:02:51.000
It will not disguise the other ingredient, but it will push them to flavour catalyst

45
00:02:51.000 --> 00:02:55.000
We can say in punctuation like it's exclamation

46
00:02:55.000 --> 00:02:57.000
Like an exclamation mark, exactly

47
00:02:57.000 --> 00:03:00.000
Matilda says pepper gives food a kick

48
00:03:00.000 --> 00:03:05.000
To give something a kick means to provide it with extra stimulation or excitement

49
00:03:05.000 --> 00:03:08.000
Pepper also makes flavours more intense

50
00:03:08.000 --> 00:03:10.000
Matilda calls it a catalyst

51
00:03:10.000 --> 00:03:15.000
Something that causes another action to start or makes it happen more quickly

52
00:03:15.000 --> 00:03:19.000
In fact, she says pepper is like an exclamation mark

53
00:03:19.000 --> 00:03:25.000
Saying something is like an exclamation mark means it shows strong emotion or excitement

54
00:03:25.000 --> 00:03:29.000
The same thing an exclamation mark does in written punctuation

55
00:03:29.000 --> 00:03:33.000
Matilda's spice shop holds pepper tasting sessions

56
00:03:33.000 --> 00:03:37.000
Where she explains to customers the origin of her peppers and how they grow

57
00:03:37.000 --> 00:03:40.000
Changing colour as they harden in the sun

58
00:03:40.000 --> 00:03:46.000
Reporter John Lawrence and attended one of these tasting sessions for BBC World Service program the food chain

59
00:03:46.000 --> 00:03:51.000
The different colours of pepper though as Matilda started to say

60
00:03:51.000 --> 00:03:57.000
Do not correspond to the different varieties but to the maturity of the pepper corns and what people do to them

61
00:03:57.000 --> 00:04:03.000
They green when they young, black when they mature and dried, red when they're very mature

62
00:04:04.000 --> 00:04:08.000
Grape pepper is an industrial creation not a botanical one

63
00:04:08.000 --> 00:04:13.000
Ground to a fine powder it is says Matilda grey dust

64
00:04:13.000 --> 00:04:15.000
She's not very keen on that one

65
00:04:15.000 --> 00:04:20.000
The colour of pepper is not determined by the variety but by its maturity

66
00:04:20.000 --> 00:04:25.000
A food's maturity describes the stage when a food is fully grown and ready to harvest

67
00:04:25.000 --> 00:04:29.000
For peppers, this is when they wrinkle and go black

68
00:04:29.000 --> 00:04:34.000
Often a pepper mill is used to grind pepper to crush it into powder

69
00:04:34.000 --> 00:04:37.000
By pressing it between two hard surfaces

70
00:04:37.000 --> 00:04:43.000
This happens with grey pepper and artificially produced pepper mix which Matilda is not keen on

71
00:04:43.000 --> 00:04:45.000
Meaning she doesn't like it

72
00:04:45.000 --> 00:04:47.000
We've learned so much about pepper

73
00:04:47.000 --> 00:04:50.000
I'll look at it differently the next time I sprinkle some on my food

74
00:04:50.000 --> 00:04:54.000
Okay now I think it's time to reveal the answer to your question

75
00:04:55.000 --> 00:05:00.000
Yes, I asked you what's unusual about food quark a white pepper from Vietnam

76
00:05:00.000 --> 00:05:05.000
I answered B because I wanted to taste like Parmesan cheese

77
00:05:05.000 --> 00:05:11.000
Well you're lucky because it is in fact B it tastes like Parmesan cheese

78
00:05:11.000 --> 00:05:12.000
Well done

79
00:05:12.000 --> 00:05:18.000
Okay, let's recap the vocabulary we've learned starting with the phrase give something a kick

80
00:05:18.000 --> 00:05:21.000
Meaning to add extra thrill or excitement

81
00:05:21.000 --> 00:05:25.000
A catalyst causes something to start or speeds it up

82
00:05:25.000 --> 00:05:31.000
If you say something is like an exclamation mark you mean it signifies strong emotion

83
00:05:31.000 --> 00:05:35.000
Surprise or excitement just like an exclamation mark does in writing

84
00:05:35.000 --> 00:05:40.000
A food's maturity refers to the stage when it's fully grown and ready for harvest

85
00:05:40.000 --> 00:05:47.000
To grind food means to crush it into powder by being pressed between two hard surfaces

86
00:05:47.000 --> 00:05:52.000
And finally if you're keen on something you like it and enjoy doing it

87
